julianthedragon
For those of u who do mastering (even as a placeholder for a better treated master later on) what does your chain normally look like?
M a n B i r d ™ 2022-11-28 3:34 PM
this might be strange but it differs haha. theres always some compressors / limiters tho. sometimes eq and such. I sometimes kinda work mastering things into the production itself (which is just a thing from me doing it all by myself so if you want to seperate that process for a different project thats also fine) (edited)
3:37 PM
But the most "standard" way i go about doing it is to route everything to a pre master channel, that way i can control some drastic volume changes from section to section before hitting compressors. I will automate that for the whole song to make it a little more consistent After that i usually hit the first compressor, this can be multiband or just overall but with multiband it ofc gives some more control over each frequency range. This one i usually set very light just to tame some extreme spikes and stuff and to be able to raise the volume a tiny bit.
3:40 PM
then after hat i will check with spectrum analyzers like tonal balance control to see if there's any parts that could be boosted or cut a bit and try some eq to see if i like that. if that's fine and to taste i will either do one more compressor if needed or go straight into the limiter. I usually dont boost the volume going into the limiter as i do like to leave dynamics for the most part. This might mean that a lot of my stuff could probs have a better perceived loudness but im still learning as well haha.
3:40 PM
for me the biggest thing is just get the production and mix as good and clean as possible on its own so the master is just that little extra spice or icing on top to make it pop that little extra
